[h3 
	" Character Selection
	$LF
]h3
[p 
	"We can choose 3 out of 6 characters, so what would we want/need?
	$LF
]p
[hr 
]hr
[p 
	"leader to determine story path and therefor difficulty, though thats debateable
	$LF
]p
[hr 
]hr
[p 
	"two strong physical fighters:
	$LF
	"in an unmodified game I can only use two controllers and the AI has certain... issues; so 
	$LF
	"(this game has 3 player control built in though it's disabled by two altered bytes)
	$LF
]p
[hr 
]hr
[p 
	"someone to deliver stat-lowering spells (optional)
	$LF
	"most necessary temporary stat boosters can be bought already early on and cost almost nothing, so no need to waste resources to deliberately learn them; if they would come with something I'd use anything, great, else no problem either
	$LF
	"stat-lowering stuff can only be learned or gotten from chest items
	$LF
	"I want at least def-down for the last boss since he has tons of health, high def and no weakness; atk-down and/or magic-down could be useful as contingencies against possible "dead end" situations (e.g. unavoidable spell that wipes the whole party)
	$LF
]p
[hr 
]hr
[p 
	"some to cast heal, oh wait,no - that's not necessary at all
	$LF
]p
[p 
	"Why no magic offensive? Spells take very long time, deal low damage, prevent the rest of the party from acting and provocate more spells as counters, that's why.
	$LF
]p
[p 
	"Depending on who we choose as lead character, we'll visit a different semi-final dungeon and get a different final boss.
	$LF
	"Cave of Darkness + Archdemon is generally thought of as the hardest of the three possible paths, so we take that.
	$LF
	"Therefor we need either Hawk or Riesz as the main character; Hawk's intro is about 1.2k frames faster, and he's more or less the 2nd best fighter in the game, 3rd without a certain lvl-up glitch.
	$LF
	"He sports a double attack and decent attack power. He'll class-change to a ninja to gain more atk than the other choice allows. As icing on the cake he gains spells that deal minor damage but at the same time debuff for the same amount a pure debuff would; I only need (or rather want) exactly one debuff: def-down, which he can use later. The optional atk/mind down is covered as well.
	$LF
]p
[p 
	"Kevin basically has to be taken, in this case as 2nd character; he's the best fighter in the game, no competition.
	$LF
	"Like Hawk he has double attack, but +1 str over him. During night time he can change into a wolf form for a 1/7 atk boost, giving him the highest atk of everyone (at least once he has gained a bit of additional str, early on it's only a very minor boost).
	$LF
	"If he is hit in wolf form, he even gains the +1/3 atk buff for free; saves a lot of items and spell animations.
	$LF
	"And to top it all off he has a glitch that's unique to him, which can basically max out his attack once I get a specific item.
	$LF
]p
[p 
	"So with two characters I've already covered everything I want, need and can make use of; Charlotte and Angela are out as they are mainly casters. That leaves us with Duran or Riesz, both are relatively strong physical fighters but bring nothing else to the table; initially I though I could make use of Riesz earlier stat-downs than Hawk but it wasn't needed at all.
	$LF
]p
[h3 
	" Class Changing:
	$LF
]h3
[p 
	"It's possible to obtain ultimate power, but before that we have the choice of doing a class change; for that we have to reach lv18 and approach either a mana stone or the goddess Statue in Mana Holy Land.
	$LF
	"A class change first increases stats to the maximum of the old class then increases the maximum and allows us to learn new spells; access to a higher level tech is given as well but those should not ever be used. 
	$LF
	"When class changing there are two new classes to change from, both with slightly different max stats, different lv2 tech and different spells.
	$LF
	"It is rumored that it's possible to class change a second time at lv 38 after gaining certain items, but this can only be complete nonsense since lv 35 is already way overleveled for finishing this game.
	$LF
]p
[h3 
	" attacking/damage stuff/formulas
	$LF
]h3
[p 
	"For each hit with a normal attack one tech point is added; lv1 tech uses 4 tech points, lv2 tech uses 7 tech points and lv3 tech uses 9 tech points. 
	$LF
	"One double attack is about 1/3 longer than a single attack but hits twice and therefor adds 2 points to the tech bar, getting us way faster to a tech.
	$LF
	"Lv1 Techs on the other hand are all more or less the same in length: twice a single attack; for double attack users those hit twice as well, and without any attack penalties.
	$LF
	"In short Hawk&Kevin get twice fast from tech to tech, while dealing twice full damage on those.
	$LF
]p
[p 
	"Damage for normal attacks is simply: atk - def
	$LF
	"Damage for normal attacks with right element (1.5 * atk) - def
	$LF
	"Damage for Lv1 techs is: (1.67 * atk) - def
	$LF
	"Damage for Lv1 techs with right element: (2.31 * atk) - def
	$LF
	"This gets very impressive with Hawk who most of the time keeps his atk ~10-20 points above the enemy's defense, so he basically deals mostly constant non-tech damage in the whole game, except against enemies that have way too low defense for their level.
	$LF
	"On the other hand his tech damage starts really low at ~35 but increases to 250+ per hit.
	$LF
]p
[p 
	"Lv2: (2 * atk) - def
	$LF
	"Lv3: (2.5 * atk) - def
	$LF
	"no element advantage, no double hits and time freeze; so... just don't
	$LF
]p
[p 
	"atk = str * weapon level + weapon constant
	$LF
	"weapon level is 2 on the starting weapons of the main character, the best buyable ones have a level of 14; the best weapons from weapon/armor seeds have level 15
	$LF
	"weapon constant is around 20 for the last weapons I use; the best weapons in game max out at 21  for Duran and 28 for Charlotte&Angela, the others in between that
	$LF
]p
[p 
	"def = vit * armor level + armor constants + other armor pieces
	$LF
	"or in other words (close to) zero for me
	$LF
]p
[p 
	"Atk caps at 370 but that can't be reached, so I'll reach it anyway.
	$LF
	"Def caps at 300 and can be semi-easily reached, so I don't.
	$LF
]p
[h3 
	" experience planning
	$LF
]h3
[p 
	"The short version is:
	$LF
	"I "need" max strength as soon as possible, no wait that would be by level 17, I want it at level 7 for the main character and 9 for the others, so let's get just that. This can be done at or directly after Tzenker without massive delays.
	$LF
	"Afterwards we'd want to aim for level 18, that should ideally be achieved near a mana stone or the goddess state in Mana Holy Land to class change soon after the level up; any later than Mana Holy Land isn't advisable as the nearest class-change opportunity would either be a massive back track or at the end of the game directly before the last boss.
	$LF
	"Initially level 18 at Lugar was missed by a few thousand experience, so it was delayed to the next chance which is already the last.
	$LF
]p
[p 
	"After leaving Mana Holy Land with class changes and lv 18 we have to face the God Beasts (that name is such an overstatement); so how much experience is to be gotten? Not much. For certain reasons I have to hit level 27 right before the 8th God-Beast; level 26 would work too, but the leeway for experience would be in the single digits.
	$LF
	"The specific reason is that Kevin has to be watched where and more importantly how he gets a level up; he needs to get it in wolf form, else I'd need about 2 minutes longer for every boss I'll still have to face till the end, probably some more, and a few minutes inbetween bosses would be added as well.
	$LF
	"And it's not a good either to *need* Kevin to fight in the rest of the room if he levels up since he'd be down to about Hawk's atk level (with the weapon I gave him) or basically zero (without said weapon).
	$LF
	"This kind of avoid to level up at a lot of situations is what dictates all non-forced fights for the rest of the game.
	$LF
]p
