[h3 
	" glitches
	$LF
]h3
[h4 
	" Skipping weapon drawing (if fight starts directly after entering screen):
	$LF
]h4
[p 
	"hold L or R + direction and let go as soon as weapons are out
	$LF
	"or pressing A+B at the exact right frame, followed by (void) in the next frame
	$LF
	"sometimes no method worked for me (e.g. uber laggy screens)
	$LF
]p
[h4 
	" Skipping weapon drawing (if fight starts while moving):
	$LF
]h4
[p 
	"Be running before the fight starts and let go of all buttons just before the weapons would be drawn out
	$LF
]p
[h4 
	" Skipping putting weapon back:
	$LF
]h4
[p 
	"Similar to above; hold B+direction and let go in time
	$LF
]p
[h4 
	" rapid attacking:
	$LF
]h4
[p 
	"normally there is a pause between two attacks/techs; by changing AI control on or off this pause can be skipped to a certain extent. This can be achieved by:
	$LF
]p
[ul 
	[li 
		" (ab)using auto attack: hold attack button until auto attack kicks in and starts the first attack then let go at least for a frame and hold attack again; shortly release attack at the start of the third/fifth/... attack to repeat - this results in a short break after the second/before the third attack but still shorter than normal
		$LF
	]li
	[li 
		" same as above but shortly release the attack button during the end of the second attack; this should result in three consecutive attacks but a full break afterwards (only for Hawk and Kevin cause of slightly longer attack animation)
		$LF
	]li
	[li 
		" using L or R to temporarily switch to one AI character; can result in both characters not doing anything if game too laggy
		$LF
	]li
	[li 
		" using Select or Start; same problem as with L/R method
		$LF
	]li
]ul
[h4 
	" Ignoring the AI:
	$LF
]h4
[p 
	"For *most* inbetween castings/skills it's a matter of randomness which can be manipulated to not be used.
	$LF
	"Some others have a sort of pattern; e.g. Dangaard will first fly a full circle around the party and then
	$LF
	"definitely do something - like throw a feather, cast a spell or in my case die.
	$LF
	"Most/all bosses have a certain "guaranteed" action they have to perform at 50% and 25% health, like using a specific spell
	$LF
	"or splitting into two new enemies (Bill/Ben) or whatever. When they reach 25% fast enough (TASing says hello)
	$LF
	"they forget their 50% action, and it's hard to do anything at 0 hp, so it's perfectly to possible to "struggle"
	$LF
	"past both spells as well. If skipping 25% action is successful, the boss usually stops moving altogether.
	$LF
	"Just be aware that if they can start their "casting stat" they will remain at 1-0-1-0-.... hp until
	$LF
	"they get their spell off.
	$LF
	"The problem here is being fast enough; once the boss decides he wants to cast that one spell, it'll be assigned an internal priority value, which goes up by time - and some skills start higher than others (e.g. Gildervine...); with certain movements/rapid actions I can semi-simulate a relatively high priority, but currently there are limits to that, so yeah...
	$LF
]p
[h4 
	" getting any stat on level up (at least up to the cap):
	$LF
]h4
[p 
	"always different, so just try-and-error; methods that helped for me so far a bit with it (nothing guaranteed!):
	$LF
	"switching screen and/or activating events before lvl-up but after getting sufficient exp (see golems x2);
	$LF
	"hitting "air" repeatedly, console-resource-heavy actions (slow-downs etc.), double/triple kills, having someone die,...
	$LF
]p
[h4 
	" Kevin's atk glitch #1:
	$LF
]h4
[p 
	"When Kevin gets a level up in wolf form and gets a strength increase the bonus to attack is LOST once he de-transforms; the attack bonus can be regotten by another lvl-up, re-equipping him any item or buying a weapon with him (if someone else buys it, it doesn't help ths case)
	$LF
]p
[h4 
	" Kevin's atk glitch #2:
	$LF
]h4
[p 
	"While Kevin is in wolf form call flamie and land somewhere, now Kevin has +1/7 atk semi-permanently, repeat until satisfied or he reaches the atk cap of 370; semi-permanent means he'll lose the bonus as soon as the game recalculates his atk, so don't have him look at a weapon (e.g. shop) and be careful when/where/how he lvls up; getting a level up in wolf form is ok, in human form is not (see above)
	$LF
]p
[p 
	"The way the last two glitches work seems to be that the game copies his current atk without stat-up/downs into a back-up value when he transforms into his wolfform.
	$LF
	"Should he get a lvl up in that form his attack is updated with his real strength, weapon level, etc. The backup value is NOT updated.
	$LF
	"Once the fight ends and he transforms back, the game simply overwrites his current atk with the backup value thereby un-doing any change to his attack (e.g. by str increase or de-bugging his attack)
	$LF
	"Or in other form
	$LF
]p
[p 
	"starting point:
	$LF
	"human form, variables: atk = 370
	$LF
]p
[p 
	"Kevin transforms:
	$LF
	"game order: store his atk in a back-up value and update atk with wolf bonus
	$LF
	"variables: atk = 422, back-up-value = 370
	$LF
	"this is probably done because rounding errors with a integer system can be fatal/game breaking;
	$LF
	"x = atk * 8 / 7 loses any number after the point (so 422.85 becomes 422)
	$LF
	"x * 7 / 8 is not necessarily the old "atk" value (369 in this case, so already wrong)
	$LF
]p
[p 
	"Kevin levels up:
	$LF
	"game order: update atk, run lvl-up script
	$LF
	"variables: atk = str * weapon multiplier + constants = 114
	$LF
	"back-up-value is not touched!
	$LF
]p
[p 
	"NOTE: here Kevin is WEAK
	$LF
]p
[p 
	"Kevin is transformed back to human:
	$LF
	"game order: give him his old atk back
	$LF
	"variables: atk = back-up-value = 370 
	$LF
]p
[p 
	"if flammie is called the game does NOT properly de-transform Kevin; ropes however do...
	$LF
]p
[h4 
